description:
Polymorphism means **one interface, many forms**. In C++, we usually get it with:

- a base class that has `virtual` methods
- derived classes that `override` those methods
- using a **base pointer or reference** to call the method

```cpp
class Animal {
public:
    virtual void speak() {
        std::cout << "...\n";
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void speak() override {
        std::cout << "woof\n";
    }
};

class Cat : public Animal {
public:
    void speak() override {
        std::cout << "meow\n";
    }
};

void makeSpeak(Animal& a) {
    a.speak(); // calls Dog::speak or Cat::speak depending on the actual object
}
```

Even though `makeSpeak` only knows about `Animal&`, the **actual object type** decides which `speak` runs.

---

## Your task

CBit OS has a small drawing system. They want to store different shapes but draw them using a base-class pointer.

- Make a base class `Shape` with a **public virtual** method `void draw()` that prints `"Shape\n"`.
- Make a class `Circle` that **inherits publicly** from `Shape` and overrides `draw` to print `"Circle\n"`.
- Make a class `Square` that **inherits publicly** from `Shape` and overrides `draw` to print `"Square\n"`.

`main` will store pointers to `Shape` but actually point them at `Circle` and `Square` objects. Polymorphism should make the correct `draw` run.

starterCode:
#include <iostream>

// define Shape, Circle, and Square here

int main() {
    Circle c;
    Square s;

    Shape* shapes[2];
    shapes[0] = &c;
    shapes[1] = &s;

    for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
        shapes[i]->draw();
    }
}
